{"id":52175,"title":"Hydra collecting for citizen scientists","title_html":"<p>Hydra collecting for citizen scientists<\/p>","image":{"source":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8yuber8x.jpg","placeholder":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8yuber8x.jpg"},"doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.bw7pphmn","doi_status":2,"uri":"hydra-collecting-for-citizen-scientists-bw7pphmn","type_id":1,"template_id":1,"published_on":1629490906,"parent_protocols":[],"parent_collections":[],"cited_protocols":[],"version_id":0,"version_data":{"id":0,"code":"bw7pphmn","parent_id":0,"parent_uri":null,"has_pending_merge_request":0,"has_approved_merge_request":0},"created_on":1628389795,"modified_on":null,"categories":null,"public":1,"is_unlisted":0,"creator":{"name":" ","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":null,"note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":null,"placeholder":null},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"journal":null,"journal_name":null,"journal_link":null,"article_citation":null,"has_versions":0,"link":null,"total_collections":0,"number_of_steps":7,"authors":[{"name":"Callen Hyland","affiliation":"University of San Diego, Biology Department","affiliations":[],"username":"m4tle152u115xle1","note":"","link":null,"image":{"source":"\/img\/avatars\/013.png","placeholder":"\/img\/avatars\/013.png"},"badges":[],"verified":1,"is_verified_user":true,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},{"name":"Kimberly Sladek","affiliation":"University of California San Diego, School of Engineering","affiliations":[],"username":null,"note":"","link":null,"image":{"source":null,"placeholder":null},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false}],"versions":[],"groups":[],"is_owner":1,"has_subprotocols":0,"is_subprotocol":0,"is_bookmarked":0,"can_claim_authorship":0,"can_accept_authorship":0,"can_be_copied":1,"can_remove_fork":1,"fork_id":null,"url":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/view\/hydra-collecting-for-citizen-scientists-bw7pphmn","forks_count":{"private":0,"public":0},"access":{"can_view":1,"can_remove":0,"can_add":0,"can_edit":0,"can_publish":0,"can_get_doi":0,"can_share":1,"can_move":1,"can_move_outside":1,"can_transfer":1,"can_download":1,"is_locked":0},"guid":"61ACD320F7F011EBB390276B836918A7","state_version_id":1701,"steps":[{"id":1229190,"guid":"5EE5D4D0F7F911EBB390276B836918A7","previous_id":null,"previous_guid":null,"modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"8BE98551E0974ACD96AD7E435B1B2FA0","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"B8E98D2CC7644B37A3C924F9983B7245","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Gather your materials:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Notebook and pen<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">White or clear plastic container (a medium-sized food storage container is ideal)<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Glass Pasteur pipette + rubber bulb<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Screw-cap vials (either glass or plastic)<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Magnifying glass, high powered reading glasses, or headband magnifier<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Optional: plastic toothbrush holder to protect your glass pipettes<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\"><\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">The Hydra Collecting Kit contains:<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Plastic food storage container<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Two glass Pasteur pipettes + one rubber bulb<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Credit card-sized magnifying glass<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Three glass screw-cap vials<\/li><\/ul><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">The Hydra Collecting Kit contains:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Plastic food storage container<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Two glass Pasteur pipettes + one rubber bulb<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Credit card-sized magnifying glass<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Three glass screw-cap vials<\/li><\/ul><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1229230,"guid":"BCB51C90F7FB11EBB390276B836918A7","previous_id":1229277,"previous_guid":"464E6120F88611EBB0D337ED2C61601D","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"8064E275D1214B6E8023097949FB3D09","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"D7529B1B1C70483BB350E8F314AD9A5D","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Select your collecting location.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Hydra are found in fresh water bodies all over the world. Look for ponds, lakes, rivers, and streams with accessible shoreline. Especially promising areas will have slowly moving water, abundant small invertebrates, and water plants to which Hydra can attach.<\/div><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8ywber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8y2ber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"961C8EE0684B4D038F8046EC4B2C374C","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8ywber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"5A84F7E5325E4B47BF5187FEBC388B5B","order_id":3,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8y2ber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1229231,"guid":"5FAC03A0F7FC11EBB390276B836918A7","previous_id":1229230,"previous_guid":"BCB51C90F7FB11EBB390276B836918A7","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2A26C2AF0584459E8834E0D9FD272D64","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"C8C99EF72AC5437CB404F1800C148EE6","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Once you are at the collecting site, record metadata about the environment:<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Name of the location<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">GPS coordinates<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Date and time<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Brief description of the location<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Any wildlife observed<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Human activity observed<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Description of the weather including air and water temperature. You can measure it if you have a thermometer, otherwise provide an estimate.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><br\/><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">You can access the metadata submission form with your mobile device and fill it out while you are in the field, or you can write everything down in your notebook and fill out the form when you get home.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/forms.gle\/cAZCiiRCyE922G5t5\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/forms.gle\/cAZCiiRCyE922G5t5<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"4685B203A1DF4BC7AB284F152763865F","order_id":2,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">To find your GPS coordinates you can drop a pin on your location using Google Maps, use the iPhone Compass app, or use a dedicated GPS smartphone app.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"42A208C82AAA425CA12D608991AAB633","order_id":3,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>It's fine to note just that there are small invertebrates present in the water, or to describe the organisms that you are familiar with (e.g. snails, water beetles), but If you want to identify aquatic invertebrates, see this guide: <\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/www.macroinvertebrates.org\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/www.macroinvertebrates.org\/<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1229232,"guid":"31C431A0F7FD11EBB390276B836918A7","previous_id":1229234,"previous_guid":"CF42CF50F80111EBB390276B836918A7","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"5D6BACF942BF47EAB0B995CB7AEBD76C","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"2B02E71B3CA2477C9916B1A5024531DD","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Did you find Hydra? If so, use the Pasteur pipette to fill a vial with water, then use the Pasteur pipette to scrape the Hydras off the surface and then suck them up and transfer them to the vial. Cap the vial leaving a small amount to air.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Record the number of Hydra you found at that location.<\/div><br\/><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8y6ber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div><br\/><br\/><br\/><br\/><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"DB699CAE2D9844E59000B19B93EDAE5B","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8y6ber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"F845C41AB3534968A1DCF15B6968E9CC","order_id":3,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">If possible, keep the Hydra in water from the site where they were collected. If you need to transfer the Hydra into a different container, you can use commercial spring water (e.g. Arrowhead). Do not use tap water or drinking water.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1229233,"guid":"201927A0F80011EBB390276B836918A7","previous_id":1229232,"previous_guid":"31C431A0F7FD11EBB390276B836918A7","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"3FF020E59BF04BEDBAE9D877FB208E9E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"ADB6076EF12C437D9771BDD4288722A2","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Make sure to fill out the metadata submission form for every site you visit. Fill out a separate form for each site, even places where you did not find Hydra (under \"number of Hydra found\" record 0 if you did not find any). <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/forms.gle\/cAZCiiRCyE922G5t5\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/forms.gle\/cAZCiiRCyE922G5t5<\/span><\/a><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">If you collected Hydra, contact callen dot hyland at gmail dot com for the next steps.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1229234,"guid":"CF42CF50F80111EBB390276B836918A7","previous_id":1229231,"previous_guid":"5FAC03A0F7FC11EBB390276B836918A7","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"7C68FBAFF50D427886FD0FAD66C9F9EE","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"A1784C0C1EE5486BBC4122D1360EF962","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Hydra attach to submerged surfaces (rocks, sticks, leaves, reeds, stems of water plants, shells) through their basal disk, so this is likely where you will find them in the water. Fill your plastic container with water, then pick up various items from the water and place them in your container. Use your magnifier to examine every side looking for Hydra. If there are none, put the items back into the water and repeat.<\/div><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8zaber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8zeber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div><br\/><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">Hydra can be difficult to spot since they are less than a centimeter long. It can be especially challenging if there is algae on the surfaces you are examining. Here are some tips for what to look for. Add a comment if you have additional suggestions.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><ul style = \"list-style-type:disc;\"><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Hydra may be extended or contracted. If extended you will notice the cylindrical body column. If contracted, they will appear spherical on the surface of the item you are examining. Either way, they will look more \"geometrical\" than the surrounding algae and debris.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Look for fine tentacles extending up into the water column.<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">Hydra can be either green or brown. In the author's experience, green Hydra are much darker green than surrounding algae and aquatic plants. Brown Hydra look tan or translucent.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><br\/><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8ziber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"CD5B479D264B46E7A1B10C16FF01DBAA","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8zaber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"2E45D4BE66A24ED78397D0D3B1F22963","order_id":3,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8zeber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"950DF35DAF8D45A1AC36EF3C2A3608F3","order_id":4,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d8ziber8x.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1229277,"guid":"464E6120F88611EBB0D337ED2C61601D","previous_id":1229190,"previous_guid":"5EE5D4D0F7F911EBB390276B836918A7","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"EE0A6C2B4EB2405A918C83A7C2B948CD","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"8A618CEE07E94563ACA1CD72F263BEF7","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Familiarize yourself with the appearance and anatomy of Hydra so you know what you are looking for.<\/div><br\/><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d58jber8x.gif\" \/><\/div><br\/><br\/><br\/><br\/><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"E7B7B5C41BAA4F8FAD0458A469208322","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/d58jber8x.gif\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"23C98212F8B54D289BB811D656066302","order_id":3,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">If you want to Google Hydra to learn more about its biology, try using terms like \"Hydra cnidaria\" or \"Hydra biology\". If you just Google \"Hydra\" most of your results will be about Greek myths and Marvel movies.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">The freshwater cnidarian Hydra has been a model system for regeneration and developmental biology for over 250 years, but much remains unknown about their biodiversity and global distribution. As a citizen scientist, you can contribute to our understanding of Hydra in the wild by becoming a \"Hydra Hunter\". All it takes is a few simple materials and a little patience.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">Collecting Hydra in the wild can be challenging. You will certainly not find them everywhere you look. Keep in mind that NOT finding Hydra is still useful information because this will help us understand the environmental factors that effect their distribution.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Metadata submission form: <\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/forms.gle\/cAZCiiRCyE922G5t5\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/forms.gle\/cAZCiiRCyE922G5t5<\/span><\/a><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">Please contact callen dot hyland at gmail dot com for more information or to receive a Hydra collecting kit.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">Hydra collecting kits were purchased with a grant to Kimberly Sladek from the University of San Diego Associated Students Government.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">Thank you to Rob Steele for helpful feedback on this protocol.<\/div><br\/><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">References:<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Campbell, R. D. (1983). Hydra Collecting. In H. M. Lenhoff (Ed.). <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Hydra: Research Methods<\/span><span>. New York: Springer Science + Business Media.<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Mart\u00ednez, D. E., et al. (2010). Phylogeny and biogeography of Hydra  (Cnidaria: Hydridae) using mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequence. <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 57<\/span><span>, 403-410. doi:10.1016\/j.ympev.2010.06.016<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1629490906}